## The Number Following You Around

Your credit score is a three-digit number between 300 and 850, and it shows up in more places than you might expect.

Landlords check it before renting you an apartment. Lenders use it to decide your mortgage rate — a difference of 100 points could mean paying $50,000 more in interest over 30 years. Insurance companies in many states use it to set premiums. Some employers even check it (with your permission) during hiring.

A score of 750 vs. 620 isn't just a number — it's the difference between getting approved and getting rejected, between a 6% interest rate and a 12% one.

The good news: once you understand how it works, improving your score is very doable.

## The Five Factors (and How Much They Matter)

The FICO score — the most widely used model — weighs five components:

### 1. Payment History (35%)
The biggest factor. Do you pay your bills on time? One missed payment can drop your score by 50–100 points. Two or three consecutive missed payments can crater it.

The fix: set up autopay for at least the minimum payment on every account. You can always pay more manually — but the autopay ensures you never miss a due date by accident.

### 2. Amounts Owed / Credit Utilization (30%)
This is the percentage of your available credit you're currently using. If you have a $5,000 credit limit and owe $2,000, your utilization is 40%.

The target: stay **below 30%** for a good score; below 10% for an excellent one. Utilization is calculated both per card and in aggregate across all cards.

This is why maxing out a card hurts your score even if you pay it off every month — the snapshot might be taken mid-cycle before you pay.

### 3. Length of Credit History (15%)
How long you've had credit, how long your oldest account has been open, and the average age of all accounts. This rewards patience.

The implication: **don't close old credit cards** even if you don't use them. A card you've had for 8 years is contributing to your average account age. Closing it shortens your history and can bump up your utilization ratio.

### 4. Credit Mix (10%)
Having different types of credit — credit cards, student loans, car loan, mortgage — demonstrates you can handle various debt types. This is a minor factor, and you shouldn't take on debt just to improve your mix.

### 5. New Credit / Hard Inquiries (10%)
Every time you apply for credit, the lender does a "hard inquiry" that slightly dings your score. Multiple applications in a short window signal financial stress.

The exception: rate shopping for a mortgage or car loan. Credit bureaus treat multiple mortgage inquiries within 14–45 days as a single inquiry, since they understand you're comparison shopping.

## Credit Report vs. Credit Score

These are different things people often confuse:

- **Credit report**: The full record of your credit history — every account, balance, payment, and inquiry. Three bureaus maintain reports: Equifax, Experian, and TransUnion.

- **Credit score**: A number calculated *from* your credit report by a scoring model (usually FICO or VantageScore).

You're entitled to one free credit report per year from each bureau at AnnualCreditReport.com (the official site — not the ones with TV commercials). Review them for errors. Mistakes — a wrong balance, an account you didn't open — are more common than people think, and they can hurt your score unfairly.

## How to Build Credit from Scratch

If you're new to credit, the catch-22 is real: you need credit history to get credit, but you need credit to build history.

**Option 1: Secured credit card.** You put down a deposit (say, $500) that becomes your credit limit. Use it for small purchases, pay it off monthly. After 6–12 months of on-time payments, you'll have a solid score and can apply for a regular card.

**Option 2: Become an authorized user.** Ask a parent or trusted family member to add you to their credit card. Their account history can appear on your report (though not all banks report authorized user accounts to bureaus).

**Option 3: Credit-builder loan.** Offered by some credit unions and community banks. You "borrow" a small amount that sits in a savings account while you make monthly payments. When the loan is paid off, you get the money and a repayment history.

## Improving a Damaged Score

If your score took a hit, here's the recovery order of operations:

1. **Bring all accounts current.** Get out of delinquency first — that stops the bleeding.
2. **Pay down high-utilization cards.** Even dropping from 80% to 40% utilization can quickly lift your score.
3. **Don't close accounts.** Even dormant cards are helping your history and utilization.
4. **Wait.** Late payments stay on your report for 7 years, but their impact fades over time. A 2-year-old missed payment hurts far less than a recent one.
5. **Don't apply for new credit while recovering.** Each hard inquiry is a small deduction; give your score time to heal.

## What a Good Score Unlocks

Here's a real example of why this matters. Say you're buying a $300,000 home with a 30-year mortgage:

- At a 760+ score: ~6.5% rate → ~$1,896/month → $382,560 total interest
- At a 620 score: ~8.2% rate → ~$2,257/month → $512,520 total interest

That's a **$130,000 difference** over the life of the loan — just from having a better credit score. The same principle applies to car loans, personal loans, and the security deposit you pay on an apartment.

Your credit score is worth investing time and attention in.

